  "method": "Build a bootstrapped, denoised preference pool before training the reward model. Start with AI-labeled preference pairs (or legacy human pairs if available) and re-query each pair multiple times using diverse labelers (e.g., several LLM judges or light-perturbed prompts) to obtain a consistency score c in [0,1]. Train a small ensemble of reward models on this pool and compute each pair’s average reward margin Δ̄ and ensemble disagreement σ_Δ. Prune contradictions (Δ̄ < 0 with high |Δ̄| and high c) and filter away trivially easy pairs (very large |Δ̄| with low σ_Δ), keeping a “core” set with moderate-to-large |Δ̄| but low σ_Δ, plus a frontier set of hard/ambiguous pairs (small |Δ̄| and/or high σ_Δ) for targeted review. If your preference data comes from multiple collection policies or labelers, estimate exposure propensities per context and source, and attach inverse-propensity weights to each pair to counter sampling bias before any filtering.\n\nTriage scarce human effort to the frontier set with a monotone reward-difference view. Fit a provisional reward model on the core set and sort all pairs by its predicted reward differences. Detect elbow/knee points on the cumulative accuracy curve to split the distribution into easy/high-confidence, uncertain, and likely-mislabeled tails. Auto-accept the easy region after a tiny spot-check, flip labels only in the most extreme low-confidence tail flagged by the curve, and allocate human annotation starting from the elbow moving into the uncertain region. Prioritize pairs by a mixture score that combines low |Δ̄|, high σ_Δ, and low c (multi-query inconsistency), which concentrates annotation on items that both the ensemble and the provisional model find confusing.\n\nTrain the reward model with a confidence- and propensity-weighted pairwise objective that is robust to outliers. Use a Bradley–Terry/DPO-style loss where each pair’s contribution is weighted by: (i) the multi-query consistency c, (ii) the inverse propensity weight to debias selection, and (iii) an uncertainty-aware downweight w = 1 / (1 + σ_Δ). Replace the standard logistic with a heavy-tailed alternative (Student’s t link or an equivalent robust loss) so rare but large residuals are softly clipped instead of dominating updates. Add a small margin-shrinkage penalty that pulls very small predicted gaps toward zero, further neutralizing ambiguous pairs. Optionally learn a per-pair temperature (heteroscedastic head) that predicts noise scale and gates the loss, trained to match observed multi-query variability.\n\nClose the loop with targeted data acquisition and safe downstream use. When collecting new model responses for comparison, rank multiple candidates per prompt with the current reward model and sample extremes (best and worst) much more often than mid-range items; this yields more informative preference updates and reduces exposure to the noisiest margin region. When using the reward model for RLHF, apply rank-based policy filtration to focus optimization on the reliably scored regions rather than mid-range plateaus, limiting over-optimization on spurious signals. Iterate: retrain the ensemble, refresh core/frontier sets, re-estimate propensities if sources shift, and spend incremental human budget only where the mixture score stays high.",
  "rationale": "This pipeline raises reward-model reliability under scarce or noisy preferences by combining three complementary controls. First, it reduces label noise upfront via multi-query consistency, ensemble disagreement filtering, and automatic detection of easy versus error-prone regions, so the model sees fewer contradictory and trivial pairs. Second, it maximizes the impact of limited human labels through principled triage on the reward-gap distribution, auditing only a tiny easy subset and concentrating annotation on ambiguous, disagreement-heavy pairs. Third, it trains with robustness and debiasing: confidence- and propensity-weighted losses, heavy-tailed error models, and margin regularization prevent outliers and selection effects from skewing the learned reward.\n\nFinally, the same reliability lens guides both data acquisition and downstream RL: sampling extremes for comparisons increases information per label, and rank-based policy filtration during RL prevents the agent from exploiting mid-range noise. Together, these steps convert limited, noisy preferences into a denoised, debiased, and robust supervisory signal that transfers to more stable policy improvement.",
