  "method": "We propose Tri-Source Uncertainty-Calibrated Reward Modeling (TRU-RM), a training loop that learns a reliable reward model rθ with three supervision streams: scarce human pairwise preferences (gold), plentiful pseudo-preferences from a pseudo-interactive demonstrator (weak), and pointwise outcome proxies from offline logs (implicit). The reward model has a shared trunk and per-source calibration heads that learn small, source-specific logit offsets to capture systematic bias. We insert a discriminative prototype layer in the pre-logit space and attach an uncertainty head uϕ that outputs a per-comparison confidence used to weight, filter, and schedule updates. A lightweight hierarchical prior encourages small source-specific biases while preserving a strong shared core, and we update the structured prior with a sampling-based gradient estimator to avoid expensive full Bayesian inference.\n\nTo expand supervision beyond scarce human labels, we train a pseudo-interactive demonstrator (PID) that, given a task instance, proposes multiple candidate outputs/trajectories and selects pseudo-winners based on accessible structure: distance-to-goal or constraint satisfaction in RL-style tasks, or rubric-based automatic judges (readability, factuality, instruction adherence) for text. The PID generates pairwise pseudo-labels across diverse difficulty levels; these are only accepted when the reward model’s uncertainty uϕ is low and the PID’s margin is high. Outcome proxies (success/penalty rates, rule violations, hallucination flags) supply pointwise targets that the reward head also regressively matches, tying the pairwise objective to measurable signals.\n\nTraining interleaves three losses with uncertainty-aware weighting: (1) a Bradley–Terry (or DPO-style) pairwise loss on human comparisons (unit weight), (2) the same loss on PID comparisons down-weighted by per-example confidence and a per-source uncertainty EMA, and (3) a pointwise regression/classification loss on outcome proxies with temperature-scaled targets. We maintain per-source moving averages of uncertainty (U-EMA) to adapt global weights online: noisier sources are down-weighted until they become reliable. Source-specific calibration heads are L2-regularized toward zero on batches that include any human-anchored examples, keeping weak-supervision biases from contaminating the shared trunk.\n\nTo spend human labels where they matter most, TRU-RM performs uncertainty-aware, efficient elicitation. For each task instance, we sample k diverse candidates, rank them with the pointwise reward, and run a small number of right-to-left adjacent comparisons among the top-k to identify only the most informative pairs to ask humans, prioritizing adjacent pairs with high disagreement or variance from uϕ. This yields near listwise refinement at O(k) human queries per instance. Periodically, we also query “anchor” comparisons drawn from a static reference set to recalibrate and audit the model.\n\nFinally, to prevent self-reward bias and drift, we include a debiasing monitor: a held-out suite scored by external references (task-specific metrics or curated gold comparisons). We regularize the reward model to maintain correlation with these references and limit candidate pool growth in self-improvement phases that would otherwise amplify stylistic or fluency artifacts. Together, the PID, uncertainty-weighted multi-source training, efficient elicitation, and debiasing yield a robust reward model from limited and noisy preference data.",
  "rationale": "TRU-RM attacks scarcity by converting abundant structure into supervision: a pseudo-demonstrator generates many high-margin comparisons, and offline outcomes supply pointwise targets. It controls noise via single-pass latent uncertainty to filter and weight pseudo-labels, plus per-source U-EMA that automatically down-weights unreliable streams. Active query selection concentrates human effort on the smallest set of pairs that maximally reduce uncertainty, using efficient adjacent comparisons to approach listwise benefits without quadratic query costs.\n\nA shared-core, source-calibrated design lets the model learn a general reward signal while explicitly modeling biases from weak supervision, and a sampling-based structured prior improves data efficiency without heavy inference. Debiasing anchored to external references prevents the classic failure mode of self-reward pipelines that overvalue fluency or style. The result is a reward model that is better calibrated, more sample-efficient, and robust to noisy or synthetic preferences.",
